**Note:** the code below is written in pseudo language

Assume we are interested in the binary representation of _f_, then there a couple of steps to be done. Let&#39;s assume that `s` contains the binary string and is initialized to &quot;0.&quot;

1. determine the sign
   ```
   s=&quot; 0.&quot;; 
   if (f &lt; 0) { s = &quot;-0.&quot;; f = -f  } 
   ```
1. determine the exponent: searching for _n_, such that _0.5 &amp;le; f &amp;times; 2&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; &lt; 1_ :
   ```
   n=0; while ( f &lt; 0.5 || f &gt;= 1) { n += (f &gt; 1 ? 1:-1); f *= (f &gt; 1 ? 0.5 : 2) }
   ```
2. determine the digits
   ```
   f *= 2
   while (f != 0) {
      if (f &gt; 0) {s += &quot;1&quot; : f -= 1 } 
      else { s += &quot;0&quot; }
      f *= 2
   }
   ```
   We assume the stopping condition to be `f != 0` as each IEEE number is numerically a finite number that is a linear combination of powers of two.
3. Print the value
   ```
   print s &quot;E&quot; n
   ``` 

Here is a quick `awk` line that does the above:

```
$ awk &#39;BEGIN { f = sqrt(42); n = 0
              s=(f&lt;0 ? &quot;-0.&quot; : &quot; 0.&quot;); f=(f&lt;0 ? -f : f)
              while ( f &lt; 0.5 || f &gt;= 1) { n += (f&gt;1 ? 1 : -1); f*=(f&gt;1?0.5:2) };
              f *= 2
              while ( f != 0 ) { s = s (f &gt; 1); f = (f - (f&gt;=1))*2 }        
              print s &quot;E&quot; n
      }&#39;
 0.110011110110001000111010010100010011000010010011000E3
```

